title.narrative: 01-03 CHILD HEALTH AND IMNCI

description.narrative: 1.3. By 2021, district health teams in selected districts have enhanced capacity to design, plan, resource and implement community sensitive primary health care, for universal access for prevention and management of common childhood illnesses with focus on malaria, pneumonia and Diarrhoea, which contributes to Child Health, Health And Development In Early Childhood And Adolescence, Strengthening Primary Health Care And High-Impact Health Interventions, Strengthening Primary Health Care And High-Impact Health Interventions (Covid). UNICEF aims to achieve this through Data, Research, Evaluation And Knowledge Management, Evaluations, Research And Data, Systems Strengthening And Institution Building, Systems Strengthening To Leave No One Behind. This contributes to the following Country Programme result: 1. By 2021, children (including newborns and adolescents) and pregnant women benefit from improved and equitable high-impact maternal, neonatal, child and adolescent health interventions and behaviors.

sector.narrative: Implementation of community based integrated prevention and management of childhood illnesses (e.g. iCCM)

description.narrative: All (100 per cent) primary health care facilities sustained adherence to the National Strategy for Integrated Management of Newborn and Childhood Illness (IMNCI) and there was no reported stock out of essential medicines including Oral Rehydration Salts (ORS) at national level.
